Lab Report #2 Solutions

DATA101: Introduction to Data Science

In this lab report, you are to again analyse the Bike Share dataset that you analysed in the previous lab report. The dataset is available under the Datasets section of the DATA101 Blackboard page. The aim of the report is to understand trends in the data using summary statistics and graphical displays.

  1. Provide an appropriate graphical display to visualise bike shares (Count) over time. Use an appropriate aggregation of hourly bike shares data to visualise the time trend, and comment on why the trend may be as shown in your graphical display.

    Solution:

    It would make most sense to aggregate into monthly totals, as shown below. A line plot of these totals is presented below and shows a cyclical pattern which is strongly related to seasons. In particular, the months of December to February correspond to low numbers of bike shares, and these are winter months for London. At the same time, June to August correspond to high numbers of bike shares, and these are summer months for London. We would naturally expect more people to want to use bicycles when the weather is a bit warmer, so that could explain higher numbers of bike shares in summer months. Additionally, we would expect tourist numbers to be higher in summer months, potentially leading to higher usage of public-use bikes.

    Producing a line plot of average temperature over time, we get the plot shown below. The plot seems to show a cyclical trend in average temperatures reflecting the seasons in London and closely matching the trend in bike shares, suggesting that the two are related and positively so (i.e., as the one increases, so does the other).

    Alternatively, we could plot both bike shares and average temperatures over time using line plots but with multiple y-axes, producing the plot shown below.     To measure the association between monthly bike shares and monthly average temperature, we can use the correlation coefficient. The correlation coefficient is \(r = 0.9344\), which is positive and very close to 1. This suggests a strong, positive relationship between monthly average temperature and monthly bike shares.

  3. Perform an appropriate analysis to compare the weather (Weather_Code) for the various seasons, being sure to provide a graphical display that can be used to effectively visualise this. Describe some of the key changes in weather that can be observed from season to season.

    Solution:

    The following table shows the proportion of hourly weather measurements that are classified according to the various weather categories for each season:

    Weather Spring Summer Autumn Winter
    Clear; mostly clear with some haze/fog/patches of fog in the vicinity 0.398725535 0.415317985 0.31512898 0.279473931
    Scattered clouds/few clouds 0.21734183 0.255071803 0.24029746 0.215829028
    Broken clouds 0.182976787 0.176658309 0.234952359 0.222639737
    Cloudy 0.07419208 0.04923638 0.086451313 0.127524659
    Rain/light rain shower 0.123805189 0.102575792 0.120613525 0.144199155
    Rain with thunderstorm 0.001593081 0.001139731 0.000232396 0.000234852
    Snowfall 0.001365498 0 0.00232396 0.010098638

    The weather categories seem to fall along a scale related to level of cloud cover and associated condensation in clouds, and it would seem reasonable to treat these as ordinal. Consequently, I have chosen to represent the comparison of weather (variable of interest) for various seasons (grouping variable) using a stacked barplot. This shows that clear weather is highest for summer and spring, followed by autumn and then winter. Summer has the least cloudy, rainy, and snowy days, whereas spring and autumn are quite similar. Winter has far more cloudy, rainy, and snowy days than other seasons.

    We can represent the relationshipi among all three of these numeric variables using a bubble plot. There are a number of ways that this could be expressed in terms of the variable corresponding to the horizontal axis, the variable corresponding to the vertical axis, and the the variable corresponding to the bubble size. I have chosen to place the average feels like temperature on the horizontal axis and average humidity on the vertical axis, and the average wind speed is used to represent bubble size, which I have scaled down in size from Excels defaults. It is not clear how wind speed relates to temperature and/or humdity, as bubble sizes do not fluctuate much (because average wind speeds do not fluctuate much) and do not show a clear trend when looking from left to right or from bottom to top in the bubble plot. There appears to be a decreasing trend in humidity as feels like temperature increases (i.e., there is a negative relationship between humidity and feels like temperature). This is likely a moderate association/correlation, as, although the decreasing trend is apparent, there is still a fair bit of scatter in the points on the bubble plot.
